  "prompt": "Why is the Beatles song (originally from The Music Man) called \u201cTill there was you\u201d and not \u201cTill there were you\u201d?",
  "response": "The Beatles song \"Till There Was You\" takes its name and lyrics from the original musical \"The Music Man\" by Meredith Willson. The wording \"Till there was you\" is a correct usage that conveys a sense of time before an individual entered one's life.\n\nHere\u2019s why it\u2019s correct:\n1. **Grammatical Structure**: \"Was\" agrees with \"you\" in singular. The phrase \"Till there was you\" refers specifically to one person coming into the speaker's life and making a special impact. It implies the presence of a single individual who changed everything.\n2. **Literal Meaning**: The song's lyrics talk about a transformation or realization that occurs upon meeting one special person. \"Till there was you\" serves to underline the unique influence of that person, which wouldn\u2019t be as personal if expressed in plural form.\n\nIn contrast, \"Till there were you\" would be grammatically incorrect and less clear in meaning, as \"were\" typically aligns with plural subjects or a different usage of singular subjects (such as in the subjunctive mood).\n\nTherefore, \"Till There Was You\" explicitly and appropriately captures the sentiment of discovering something essential and beautiful solely because of one unique individual\u2019s presence.",
